== Quinoa ==

Adjust rack to top position and preheat oven to 450 degrees. Wash and dry produce.

Peel and mince or grate @Ginger{1%thumb} until you have 1 tsp (2 tsp for 4 servings).

Heat a drizzle of @Cooking Oil{1%tsp} in a small #pot{} over medium-high heat. Add ginger; cook, stirring, until fragrant, ~{30%seconds}.

Stir in 1 cup water (2 cups for 4), @Veggie Stock Concentrate{1}, and half the @Soy Sauce{2%tablespoon} (you'll use the rest in step 3). Bring to a boil, then stir in @White Quinoa{1/2%cup}. Cover and reduce to a low simmer. Cook until quinoa is tender and water has evaporated, ~{15-20%minutes}.

Keep covered off heat until ready to serve.

== Smashed Cucumber ==

While quinoa cooks, place @Persian Cucumber{1} under a plate; press down until cucumber splits open. Cut cucumber into 1-inch pieces. Cut @Broccoli Florets{8%ounce} into bite-size pieces if necessary.

In a medium #bowl{}, combine @Rice Wine Vinegar{5%teaspoon}, @Sugar{1%tsp}, and @Salt{1/2%tsp}. Stir in cucumber and up to half the @Sesame Seeds{1%tablespoon} (save the rest for serving). Set aside, stirring occasionally, until ready to serve.

== Roasted Broccoli ==

In a large bowl, whisk together half the @Sweet Thai Chili Sauce{1%ounce}, remaining soy sauce, and a drizzle of oil. Add broccoli and stir to coat; spread out on a foil-lined #baking sheet{}.

Roast on top rack until browned and tender, ~{12-15%minutes}.

Once broccoli is done, carefully return to bowl used for seasoning.

== Spicy Mayo ==

Meanwhile, in a small bowl, combine @Mayonnaise{2%tablespoon} and remaining chili sauce. Add water 1 tsp at a time until mixture reaches a drizzling consistency. Season with @Salt{} to taste.

== Fried Eggs ==

Heat a drizzle of oil in a medium, preferably nonstick, pan over medium-high heat. Once hot, crack @Eggs{2} into pan and cover. Fry eggs to preference. Season with salt and @Pepper{}. Turn off heat.

== Assembly ==

Fluff quinoa with a #fork{}; stir in @Butter{1%tablespoon} until melted. Season with salt.

Divide quinoa between bowls and top with broccoli, smashed cucumber, and eggs in separate sections. Drizzle with spicy mayo. Garnish with as many remaining sesame seeds as you like and serve.

> A fun fact about quinoa? It's actually a protein-packed seed! And, it forms the base for hearty, vegetarian bowls.

> The hardest part: getting a little bit of everything onto your fork.